#X text 122 384 AMPLITUDE MODULATION -->;
#X text 35 62 In modulation synthesis \, we consider one signal - called 'carrier' - to be modulated by another - called a 'modulator'. Here we have an amplitude modulation example where both the carrier and modulator signals are sine wave oscillators. This is "classic" amplitude modulation because the modulator signal has a DC-Offset so that it is "unipolar" and only has positive values (from 0 to 1). Hence \, the modulation range goes from silence (0) to the original amplitude (1)., f 82;
#X text 35 158 We can hear a rather complex output from the interaction of these waves \, which will be explained in detail soon. Even though it can generate more complex sound and the fact that it's common to see it as a synthesis topic \, Amplitude Modulation (AM) is not a real syntehsis technique to generate complex timbre (like it's the case for frequency modulation). We'll also see how Amplitude Modulation \, more precisely Ring Modulation (the next example) is widely used as an effects processor., f 82;
